Question: Return all palindrome strings from a list (ignoring case).

Input:
List<String> vals = Arrays.asList("Level", "world", "civic", "java");

Solutions:-

Java 8 Streams return palindromes (ignoring case) using filter with custom palindrome check. For input ["Level", "world", "civic", "java"], returns ["Level", "civic"].

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream → lowercase → filter(isPalindrome) → collect(toList()).

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class PalindromeFilter {
    
    private static boolean isPalindrome(String s) {
        String lower = s.toLowerCase();
        int left = 0, right = lower.length() - 1;
        while (left < right) {
            if (lower.charAt(left++) != lower.charAt(right--)) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
    
    public static List<String> findPalindromes(List<String> vals) {
        return vals.stream()
                   .filter(PalindromeFilter::isPalindrome)
                   .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> vals = Arrays.asList("Level", "world", "civic", "java");
        List<String> palindromes = findPalindromes(vals);
        System.out.println(palindromes);  // [Level, civic]
    }
}

#Another Apporach:-
vals.stream()
    .filter(s -> {
        String lower = s.toLowerCase();
        return lower.equals(new StringBuilder(lower).reverse().toString());
    })
    .forEach(System.out::println);

#Thought Process
Two-pointer palindrome check: Compare chars from both ends moving inward. Case-insensitive via toLowerCase(). Preserve original casing in output (filter on lowered copy). O(n) per string.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: []
Empty strings: "" is palindrome ✓
Single chars: "a" is palindrome ✓
Null list: NPE on stream()
Null elements: NPE in toLowerCase()
All palindromes: Returns copy
No palindromes: []
